---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Quick Start - ColorClip Pro Documentation"
  description="Get started with ColorClip Pro in minutes"
>
  <h1>Quick Start Guide</h1>

  <p>
    This guide walks you through the basics of ColorClip Pro. You'll be picking and
    organizing colors in just a few minutes.
  </p>

  <img
    src="/teaser_videos/00_Draggable_Color_Drawer.gif"
    alt="ColorClip Pro color drawer overview"
    class="doc-screenshot"
  />
  <span class="doc-screenshot-caption">ColorClip Pro's draggable color drawer sits on top of any application</span>

  <!-- ─── Step 1 ─── -->
  <h2>Step 1: Create Your First Palette</h2>

  <p>
    When you first launch ColorClip Pro, you'll see an empty palette. Each palette can
    hold up to 256 color swatches.
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>Click the <strong>+ New Palette</strong> button (or press <code>Cmd+N</code> / <code>Ctrl+N</code>)</li>
    <li>Give your palette a name (e.g., "Brand Colors")</li>
    <li>Empty swatch slots appear ready for colors</li>
  </ol>

  <img
    src="/teaser_videos/04_Unlimited_Palettes.gif"
    alt="Creating and switching between unlimited palettes"
    class="doc-screenshot"
  />
  <span class="doc-screenshot-caption">You can create unlimited palettes and switch between them instantly</span>

  <!-- ─── Step 2 ─── -->
  <h2>Step 2: Add a Color</h2>

  <p>There are three ways to add a color to your palette:</p>

  <h3>Method 1: Color Picker</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Click an empty swatch slot</li>
    <li>Choose from the color wheel or use the sliders</li>
    <li>Switch between multiple color models (HEX, RGB, HSV, etc.)</li>
    <li>The color saves automatically to that slot</li>
  </ol>

  <img
    src="/teaser_videos/02_Multiple_Color_Models.gif"
    alt="Switching between color models in the picker"
    class="doc-screenshot"
  />
  <span class="doc-screenshot-caption">Switch between HEX, RGB, HSV, and more color models without losing your color</span>

  <h3>Method 2: Eyedropper</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Click the eyedropper button or press <code>Cmd+E</code> (Mac) / <code>Ctrl+E</code> (Windows)</li>
    <li>Your screen dims and shows a magnified preview</li>
    <li>Adjust the eyedropper size for the precision you need</li>
    <li>Click anywhere on screen to capture that color</li>
  </ol>

  <img
    src="/teaser_videos/06_Fuzzy_Eyedropper.gif"
    alt="Fuzzy eyedropper picking colors from the screen"
    class="doc-screenshot"
  />
  <span class="doc-screenshot-caption">The fuzzy eyedropper lets you adjust capture radius — great for anti-aliased or blurred edges</span>

  <h3>Method 3: Paste a HEX Code</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Copy any HEX color code (e.g., <code>#FF5733</code>)</li>
    <li>Click an empty swatch slot</li>
    <li>Paste the code directly into the color input</li>
  </ol>

  <!-- ─── Step 3 ─── -->
  <h2>Step 3: Organize Your Colors</h2>

  <h3>Label Swatches</h3>
  <p>
    Right-click any swatch and choose <strong>Edit Label</strong> to give it a meaningful
    name like "Brand Primary" or "Accent Blue". Labels appear on hover.
  </p>

  <img
    src="/teaser_videos/09_Swatch_Label.gif"
    alt="Adding labels to color swatches"
    class="doc-screenshot"
  />
  <span class="doc-screenshot-caption">Swatch labels make it easy to identify colors at a glance</span>

  <h3>Copy & Paste Swatches</h3>
  <p>
    Right-click any swatch to copy it, then paste it into another slot or palette.
    Great for duplicating colors across projects.
  </p>

  <img
    src="/teaser_videos/08_Swatch_Copy_Paste.gif"
    alt="Copying and pasting swatches between palettes"
    class="doc-screenshot"
  />
  <span class="doc-screenshot-caption">Copy and paste swatches between any palettes</span>

  <h3>Rearrange Swatches</h3>
  <p>Drag and drop swatches to reorder them. Your layout is saved automatically.</p>

  <h3>Delete Swatches</h3>
  <p>Right-click a swatch and select <strong>Delete</strong>, or press <code>Delete</code> when a swatch is selected.</p>

  <!-- ─── Step 4 ─── -->
  <h2>Step 4: Copy Colors</h2>

  <p>
    Click any swatch to instantly copy its color value. ColorClip Pro supports automatic
    format conversion — see your color in every format simultaneously.
  </p>

  <img
    src="/teaser_videos/05_Automatic_Value_Conversion.gif"
    alt="Automatic color value conversion between formats"
    class="doc-screenshot"
  />
  <span class="doc-screenshot-caption">Change the color model and your value updates instantly — no manual conversion needed</span>

  <p>Supported copy formats:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>HEX</strong> — <code>#FF5733</code></li>
    <li><strong>RGB</strong> — <code>rgb(255, 87, 51)</code></li>
    <li><strong>HSV</strong> — <code>hsv(11, 80%, 100%)</code></li>
    <li><strong>Normalized RGB</strong> — <code>1.0, 0.34, 0.2</code> (for game engines)</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="step-callout">
    <strong>Tip:</strong> Change your default copy format in <strong>Settings → Copy Format</strong>.
    Game developers: use Normalized RGB for Unity and Unreal Engine.
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Step 5 ─── -->
  <h2>Step 5: Enable Cloud Sync (Optional)</h2>

  <p>
    Sync your palettes across all your devices — Windows and Mac — with a single click.
    No complicated setup required.
  </p>

  <img
    src="/teaser_videos/11_Easy_Cloud_Sync.gif"
    alt="Setting up cloud sync in ColorClip Pro"
    class="doc-screenshot"
  />
  <span class="doc-screenshot-caption">Cloud sync setup takes seconds and works across Windows and macOS</span>

  <ol>
    <li>Click the cloud icon in the top-right corner</li>
    <li>Sign in with Google, GitHub, or Discord</li>
    <li>Your palettes sync automatically in real time</li>
    <li>Install ColorClip Pro on other devices and sign in with the same account</li>
  </ol>

  <img
    src="/teaser_videos/07_Cross_OS_Cloud_Sync.gif"
    alt="Cross-platform cloud sync between Windows and Mac"
    class="doc-screenshot"
  />
  <span class="doc-screenshot-caption">Your palettes stay in sync across Windows and macOS — changes appear instantly on all devices</span>

  <div class="step-callout">
    <strong>Prefer offline?</strong> ColorClip Pro also supports fully offline mode with
    folder sync — drop your palette files into any shared folder (Dropbox, Google Drive,
    iCloud, OneDrive) and it syncs automatically without an account.
  </div>

  <img
    src="/teaser_videos/01_Fully_Offline_Mode.gif"
    alt="Fully offline mode with folder sync"
    class="doc-screenshot"
  />
  <span class="doc-screenshot-caption">Offline mode: point ColorClip Pro at any sync folder — no login required</span>

  <!-- ─── Dark Mode ─── -->
  <h2>Step 6: Customize Your Theme</h2>

  <p>
    ColorClip Pro offers four levels of dark mode so it fits seamlessly into your
    workspace, whether you prefer a bright UI or a deep dark one.
  </p>

  <img
    src="/teaser_videos/03_Multiple_Dark_Modes.gif"
    alt="Multiple dark mode levels in ColorClip Pro"
    class="doc-screenshot"
  />
  <span class="doc-screenshot-caption">Choose from light, dim, dark, and deep dark themes in Settings → Appearance</span>

  <!-- ─── Keyboard Shortcuts ─── -->
  <h2>Keyboard Shortcuts</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Action</th>
        <th>macOS</th>
        <th>Windows</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Eyedropper</td>
        <td><code>Cmd+E</code></td>
        <td><code>Ctrl+E</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>New Palette</td>
        <td><code>Cmd+N</code></td>
        <td><code>Ctrl+N</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Settings</td>
        <td><code>Cmd+,</code></td>
        <td><code>Ctrl+,</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Delete Swatch</td>
        <td><code>Delete</code></td>
        <td><code>Delete</code></td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- ─── Next Steps ─── -->
  <h2>Next Steps</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Explore <a href="/docs/features/palettes">advanced palette features</a></li>
    <li>Learn about <a href="/docs/faq">frequently asked questions</a></li>
    <li>See all <a href="/releases">release notes</a></li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
